 depend on the stimulus being polarized; the observed decline in amplitude is probably caused by physiological changes.</p></div><a class="close-reveal-modal" href="javascript:;"><i class="icon-general-close"> </i></a></div>
                </div>
                <div id="17082486" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082482">
                    
                    <p>The ERG responses to more intense stimuli (approximately 4 <em>μ</em>W or more) were usually superimposed with oscillatory potentials. The change in the shape of the ERG responses, as reported by <a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325C14" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325C14" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Delius <em>et al</em>. (1976)</a>, is probably caused by the behaviour of oscillatory potentials, so we studied them carefully. An example of this kind of analysis is shown in <a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="link link-reveal link-table xref-fig">Fig. 3</a>. <a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="link link-reveal link-table xref-fig">Fig. 3A,B</a> shows that the use of control measurements is mandatory, because if, as in <a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="link link-reveal link-table xref-fig">Fig. 3B</a>, the responses to the test stimuli were plotted without control ERGs, some kind of periodicity could be inferred. This means that presenting the stimulus conditions in a randomized order (which is a well-established way of carrying out such experiments) is not sufficient to correct for variations in time.</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082487" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082482">
                    
                    <a id = "17082487" scrollto-destination="17082487"></a><div data-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="fig fig-section"><div class="label fig-label">Fig. 3.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="fig-link"><img class="content-image" src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=EncBoxyBp2BlQch3UDeqVbwMAPymoZ4oLimzXEHHpUqE~VHABoMU4PvhHDvEZxtGRIstuQFACrl2fSDIPo2ik3Se5bdkf6k8px2h961ok9baU2y6ZDvcMZU26Ges~t3sspzpdRZBME7OGvY~L2miZ6tHtETKqSr~nhEnzKSsvRDchQWpKL~hPxnGOJBL9s~qfaYifTRCijTh8LfyYyugNX0P2J9mv4E54Wwy2WZncBOt6U1GIYjL1EQ6rz6mCrkjMdUrinuuSbn0X1fMeahh74B201EDJNN4~ZXacVMTXeaYjz1aM2LroHCoELdv6E19BH~uexGZrpcpaYP3rFCEiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" data-src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=EncBoxyBp2BlQch3UDeqVbwMAPymoZ4oLimzXEHHpUqE~VHABoMU4PvhHDvEZxtGRIstuQFACrl2fSDIPo2ik3Se5bdkf6k8px2h961ok9baU2y6ZDvcMZU26Ges~t3sspzpdRZBME7OGvY~L2miZ6tHtETKqSr~nhEnzKSsvRDchQWpKL~hPxnGOJBL9s~qfaYifTRCijTh8LfyYyugNX0P2J9mv4E54Wwy2WZncBOt6U1GIYjL1EQ6rz6mCrkjMdUrinuuSbn0X1fMeahh74B201EDJNN4~ZXacVMTXeaYjz1aM2LroHCoELdv6E19BH~uexGZrpcpaYP3rFCEiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Latencies of the oscillatory potentials, with the lowest trace depicting the latencies of the peak of the first oscillatory potential, the next highest trace those of the next peak, etc. In A, the latencies are shown in the order in which the ERGs were measured (denoted by the sequence number of the ERG). The squares indicate the responses to polarized stimuli with varying E-vector orientations (θ), the open circles denote the responses to stimuli polarized at a fixed angle of 60°, and the reference stimuli. The same latency data are replotted in B, but as a function of the angle of the E-vector. The stimuli were monochromatic light flashes (123 ms; centre wavelength 575 nm; radiant power 20 μW; number of photons per flash 7.1×1012), which were given continuously throughout the experiment, at a rate of 1 s-1. The area 20 ° below the fovea was stimulated. ERGs were recorded without the filled circles show the responses to additional illumination; between the recording periods (each lasting 10 min), an adaptation lamp (100 lx at the eye of the pigeon) was turned on for 5 min. When the responses to the polarized test stimuli were plotted alone, a dependency on the orientation of the E-vector could be inferred. However, because the responses to the unpolarized and to the polarized stimuli, whose E-vector orientation was fixed, vary in the same manner, such a conclusion is not warranted." path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" /></a><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a section="17082487" class="fig-view-orig" href="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=JL~8BV6OQF65s4rV8s1xIhU1J8TlXuBpDEo58HCyYpxgK6cJhLQOijaht8g6qdaQtRPaSkoax0g~ODxnVu~qZWXIGUxAUseGGhYbl-y2DpZ~tFLSWuve0nNuB7VJxGVEVNQnprpJ1fXVpjQxTJqwUKHYvPEZdmSu2kaYaQLF9meF-IZrEU6d3RHwGRHV47lNCJT8s5naRH-EapjCZmEGak361g~m3cRf6vRwZV33Y5rg8Wigm5x20LSV2WmkKnVJc1CmhoRefJCDK-dQ2MLpY8ZZl6E3-jSla2k7xLeuagMolYwYsLMWod3Q2kc2dCj0udCg8vq80eeidO0poIk4KA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" target="_blank">View large</a><a section="17082487" href="//cob.silverchair-cdn.com/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&Signature=JL~8BV6OQF65s4rV8s1xIhU1J8TlXuBpDEo58HCyYpxgK6cJhLQOijaht8g6qdaQtRPaSkoax0g~ODxnVu~qZWXIGUxAUseGGhYbl-y2DpZ~tFLSWuve0nNuB7VJxGVEVNQnprpJ1fXVpjQxTJqwUKHYvPEZdmSu2kaYaQLF9meF-IZrEU6d3RHwGRHV47lNCJT8s5naRH-EapjCZmEGak361g~m3cRf6vRwZV33Y5rg8Wigm5x20LSV2WmkKnVJc1CmhoRefJCDK-dQ2MLpY8ZZl6E3-jSla2k7xLeuagMolYwYsLMWod3Q2kc2dCj0udCg8vq80eeidO0poIk4KA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=17082487&ar=7054&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=1000009" class="download-slide" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" target="_blank">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p>Latencies of the oscillatory potentials, with the lowest trace depicting the latencies of the peak of the first oscillatory potential, the next highest trace those of the next peak, etc. In A, the latencies are shown in the order in which the ERGs were measured (denoted by the sequence number of the ERG). The squares indicate the responses to polarized stimuli with varying <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector orientations (<em>θ</em>), the open circles denote the responses to stimuli polarized at a fixed angle of 60°, and the reference stimuli. The same latency data are replotted in B, but as a function of the angle of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector. The stimuli were monochromatic light flashes (123 ms; centre wavelength 575 nm; radiant power 20 <em>μ</em>W; number of photons per flash 7.1×10<sup>12</sup>), which were given continuously throughout the experiment, at a rate of 1 s<sup>-1</sup>. The area 20 ° below the fovea was stimulated. ERGs were recorded without the filled circles show the responses to additional illumination; between the recording periods (each lasting 10 min), an adaptation lamp (100 lx at the eye of the pigeon) was turned on for 5 min. When the responses to the polarized test stimuli were plotted alone, a dependency on the orientation of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector could be inferred. However, because the responses to the unpolarized and to the polarized stimuli, whose <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector orientation was fixed, vary in the same manner, such a conclusion is not warranted.</p></div></div><div id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" content-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="fig fig-modal reveal-modal" data-reveal="data-reveal"><div class="label fig-label">Fig. 3.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3" class="fig-link"><img class="content-image" src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=EncBoxyBp2BlQch3UDeqVbwMAPymoZ4oLimzXEHHpUqE~VHABoMU4PvhHDvEZxtGRIstuQFACrl2fSDIPo2ik3Se5bdkf6k8px2h961ok9baU2y6ZDvcMZU26Ges~t3sspzpdRZBME7OGvY~L2miZ6tHtETKqSr~nhEnzKSsvRDchQWpKL~hPxnGOJBL9s~qfaYifTRCijTh8LfyYyugNX0P2J9mv4E54Wwy2WZncBOt6U1GIYjL1EQ6rz6mCrkjMdUrinuuSbn0X1fMeahh74B201EDJNN4~ZXacVMTXeaYjz1aM2LroHCoELdv6E19BH~uexGZrpcpaYP3rFCEiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" data-src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=EncBoxyBp2BlQch3UDeqVbwMAPymoZ4oLimzXEHHpUqE~VHABoMU4PvhHDvEZxtGRIstuQFACrl2fSDIPo2ik3Se5bdkf6k8px2h961ok9baU2y6ZDvcMZU26Ges~t3sspzpdRZBME7OGvY~L2miZ6tHtETKqSr~nhEnzKSsvRDchQWpKL~hPxnGOJBL9s~qfaYifTRCijTh8LfyYyugNX0P2J9mv4E54Wwy2WZncBOt6U1GIYjL1EQ6rz6mCrkjMdUrinuuSbn0X1fMeahh74B201EDJNN4~ZXacVMTXeaYjz1aM2LroHCoELdv6E19BH~uexGZrpcpaYP3rFCEiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Latencies of the oscillatory potentials, with the lowest trace depicting the latencies of the peak of the first oscillatory potential, the next highest trace those of the next peak, etc. In A, the latencies are shown in the order in which the ERGs were measured (denoted by the sequence number of the ERG). The squares indicate the responses to polarized stimuli with varying E-vector orientations (θ), the open circles denote the responses to stimuli polarized at a fixed angle of 60°, and the reference stimuli. The same latency data are replotted in B, but as a function of the angle of the E-vector. The stimuli were monochromatic light flashes (123 ms; centre wavelength 575 nm; radiant power 20 μW; number of photons per flash 7.1×1012), which were given continuously throughout the experiment, at a rate of 1 s-1. The area 20 ° below the fovea was stimulated. ERGs were recorded without the filled circles show the responses to additional illumination; between the recording periods (each lasting 10 min), an adaptation lamp (100 lx at the eye of the pigeon) was turned on for 5 min. When the responses to the polarized test stimuli were plotted alone, a dependency on the orientation of the E-vector could be inferred. However, because the responses to the unpolarized and to the polarized stimuli, whose E-vector orientation was fixed, vary in the same manner, such a conclusion is not warranted." path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" /></a><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a section="17082487" class="fig-view-orig" href="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=JL~8BV6OQF65s4rV8s1xIhU1J8TlXuBpDEo58HCyYpxgK6cJhLQOijaht8g6qdaQtRPaSkoax0g~ODxnVu~qZWXIGUxAUseGGhYbl-y2DpZ~tFLSWuve0nNuB7VJxGVEVNQnprpJ1fXVpjQxTJqwUKHYvPEZdmSu2kaYaQLF9meF-IZrEU6d3RHwGRHV47lNCJT8s5naRH-EapjCZmEGak361g~m3cRf6vRwZV33Y5rg8Wigm5x20LSV2WmkKnVJc1CmhoRefJCDK-dQ2MLpY8ZZl6E3-jSla2k7xLeuagMolYwYsLMWod3Q2kc2dCj0udCg8vq80eeidO0poIk4KA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" target="_blank">View large</a><a section="17082487" href="//cob.silverchair-cdn.com/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f3.png?Expires=1716296304&Signature=JL~8BV6OQF65s4rV8s1xIhU1J8TlXuBpDEo58HCyYpxgK6cJhLQOijaht8g6qdaQtRPaSkoax0g~ODxnVu~qZWXIGUxAUseGGhYbl-y2DpZ~tFLSWuve0nNuB7VJxGVEVNQnprpJ1fXVpjQxTJqwUKHYvPEZdmSu2kaYaQLF9meF-IZrEU6d3RHwGRHV47lNCJT8s5naRH-EapjCZmEGak361g~m3cRf6vRwZV33Y5rg8Wigm5x20LSV2WmkKnVJc1CmhoRefJCDK-dQ2MLpY8ZZl6E3-jSla2k7xLeuagMolYwYsLMWod3Q2kc2dCj0udCg8vq80eeidO0poIk4KA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=17082487&ar=7054&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=1000009" class="download-slide" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F3.tif" target="_blank">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p>Latencies of the oscillatory potentials, with the lowest trace depicting the latencies of the peak of the first oscillatory potential, the next highest trace those of the next peak, etc. In A, the latencies are shown in the order in which the ERGs were measured (denoted by the sequence number of the ERG). The squares indicate the responses to polarized stimuli with varying <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector orientations (<em>θ</em>), the open circles denote the responses to stimuli polarized at a fixed angle of 60°, and the reference stimuli. The same latency data are replotted in B, but as a function of the angle of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector. The stimuli were monochromatic light flashes (123 ms; centre wavelength 575 nm; radiant power 20 <em>μ</em>W; number of photons per flash 7.1×10<sup>12</sup>), which were given continuously throughout the experiment, at a rate of 1 s<sup>-1</sup>. The area 20 ° below the fovea was stimulated. ERGs were recorded without the filled circles show the responses to additional illumination; between the recording periods (each lasting 10 min), an adaptation lamp (100 lx at the eye of the pigeon) was turned on for 5 min. When the responses to the polarized test stimuli were plotted alone, a dependency on the orientation of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector could be inferred. However, because the responses to the unpolarized and to the polarized stimuli, whose <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector orientation was fixed, vary in the same manner, such a conclusion is not warranted.</p></div><a class="close-reveal-modal" href="javascript:;"><i class="icon-general-close"> </i></a></div>
                </div>
                <div id="17082488" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082482">
                    
                    <p>We have also conducted experiments to check the influence of short periods of dark adaptation. These experiments show that the periods of darkness during which we recorded the responses were too short to account for changes in the ERG that could be explained as a result of the state of polarization of the stimulus (<a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" class="link link-reveal link-table xref-fig">Fig. 4</a>).</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082489" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082482">
                    
                    <a id = "17082489" scrollto-destination="17082489"></a><div data-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" class="fig fig-section"><div class="label fig-label">Fig. 4.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" class="fig-link"><img class="content-image" src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d596rkB7Ppy5OcQY8FNQ20XBG5joRelXmOedEGo-pjQH0y2tesh-czrBDzBVOXJjvTn7MTD1w5q68oWaJ5mKvX3EuYVe4JUCV-QtrzAUziPF5iP~lh1aA07xK9VwZEESQB1jcrMsT4DPmwJPBXeSn9XwzeITn6qZ4jnA-LrTJA2AbfdAmewbqVDSS1fgYdXYRD8BlmMjHYj4WOjUbI3ddAwvJrKvLq-Ie~RxPo9NnwuTgYDYvjT9LxL~B44ZZJOsTHHW6cg5JCRaTYFzbl4DX0z51Eoc9UyS019tGmU8bSIVq2tqXyT8A1dOgHCteF7~-U38txu~H3kARg7iivuNOA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" data-src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d596rkB7Ppy5OcQY8FNQ20XBG5joRelXmOedEGo-pjQH0y2tesh-czrBDzBVOXJjvTn7MTD1w5q68oWaJ5mKvX3EuYVe4JUCV-QtrzAUziPF5iP~lh1aA07xK9VwZEESQB1jcrMsT4DPmwJPBXeSn9XwzeITn6qZ4jnA-LrTJA2AbfdAmewbqVDSS1fgYdXYRD8BlmMjHYj4WOjUbI3ddAwvJrKvLq-Ie~RxPo9NnwuTgYDYvjT9LxL~B44ZZJOsTHHW6cg5JCRaTYFzbl4DX0z51Eoc9UyS019tGmU8bSIVq2tqXyT8A1dOgHCteF7~-U38txu~H3kARg7iivuNOA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Responses to identical stimuli after dark and light adaptation. Flashes of white light (N=32; duration 130 ms; radiant power 20 μW; number of photons per flash 6.8×1012) were used. The ERGs obtained after increasing periods of darkness are depicted in A, whereas in B the matching control ERGs are shown (for the shifted vertically). The stimulation regimen was as follows: after 5 min of light adaptation (100 lx at the eye level of the pigeon), a control response was obtained. Then followed a period of darkness (given beside each trace in minutes), at the end of which an ERG was again measured. This was repeated a number of times with longer dark adaptation times. This type of measurement was often carried out prior to examining the effects of polarized light. It is obvious that the effect of dark adaptation under these circumstances is negligible, even for the longer periods of darkness. Although this procedure is not suited for gauging the rate of dark adaptation (the flashes were so intense that light adaptation was induced during the measurement of the ERG), it appears that dark adaptation is a slow process." path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" /></a><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a section="17082489" class="fig-view-orig" href="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d~W00h7IpuUDobh6wWeG~W-VsKn490O~gijJd5B-JD-B7CEB6uKe4J8Sx~RlbFsZypjvk6SAtFeceI32U0cV5l8tbZz9QrzdZFsoC-fSfhP1khoa~u9BQpVJ0i~P9t6jcmZYN68sQ11exhnU5jd1wX1zxzcLz9dMtOy~mIpnqrWErqb3~uMicZZnb4de-0LNsZDdZsm81S-kM0AK7bUJsVGQakcAm8Y-gA9KMOYObvOWshwVjDUw0ITyW3VLSXqU9FV4iZ8xkfp3tQ0c9sXNE5fhYgkYuXNVgPjYpCi2lcKlUKq19HX-wE86V6htV3QszOI6onuRM4mlkAQeKazYCg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" target="_blank">View large</a><a section="17082489" href="//cob.silverchair-cdn.com/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&Signature=d~W00h7IpuUDobh6wWeG~W-VsKn490O~gijJd5B-JD-B7CEB6uKe4J8Sx~RlbFsZypjvk6SAtFeceI32U0cV5l8tbZz9QrzdZFsoC-fSfhP1khoa~u9BQpVJ0i~P9t6jcmZYN68sQ11exhnU5jd1wX1zxzcLz9dMtOy~mIpnqrWErqb3~uMicZZnb4de-0LNsZDdZsm81S-kM0AK7bUJsVGQakcAm8Y-gA9KMOYObvOWshwVjDUw0ITyW3VLSXqU9FV4iZ8xkfp3tQ0c9sXNE5fhYgkYuXNVgPjYpCi2lcKlUKq19HX-wE86V6htV3QszOI6onuRM4mlkAQeKazYCg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=17082489&ar=7054&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=1000009" class="download-slide" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" target="_blank">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p>Responses to identical stimuli after dark and light adaptation. Flashes of white light (<em>N</em>=32; duration 130 ms; radiant power 20 <em>μ</em>W; number of photons per flash 6.8×10<sup>12</sup>) were used. The ERGs obtained after increasing periods of darkness are depicted in A, whereas in B the matching control ERGs are shown (for the shifted vertically). The stimulation regimen was as follows: after 5 min of light adaptation (100 lx at the eye level of the pigeon), a control response was obtained. Then followed a period of darkness (given beside each trace in minutes), at the end of which an ERG was again measured. This was repeated a number of times with longer dark adaptation times. This type of measurement was often carried out prior to examining the effects of polarized light. It is obvious that the effect of dark adaptation under these circumstances is negligible, even for the longer periods of darkness. Although this procedure is not suited for gauging the rate of dark adaptation (the flashes were so intense that light adaptation was induced during the measurement of the ERG), it appears that dark adaptation is a slow process.</p></div></div><div id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" content-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" class="fig fig-modal reveal-modal" data-reveal="data-reveal"><div class="label fig-label">Fig. 4.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4" class="fig-link"><img class="content-image" src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d596rkB7Ppy5OcQY8FNQ20XBG5joRelXmOedEGo-pjQH0y2tesh-czrBDzBVOXJjvTn7MTD1w5q68oWaJ5mKvX3EuYVe4JUCV-QtrzAUziPF5iP~lh1aA07xK9VwZEESQB1jcrMsT4DPmwJPBXeSn9XwzeITn6qZ4jnA-LrTJA2AbfdAmewbqVDSS1fgYdXYRD8BlmMjHYj4WOjUbI3ddAwvJrKvLq-Ie~RxPo9NnwuTgYDYvjT9LxL~B44ZZJOsTHHW6cg5JCRaTYFzbl4DX0z51Eoc9UyS019tGmU8bSIVq2tqXyT8A1dOgHCteF7~-U38txu~H3kARg7iivuNOA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" data-src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d596rkB7Ppy5OcQY8FNQ20XBG5joRelXmOedEGo-pjQH0y2tesh-czrBDzBVOXJjvTn7MTD1w5q68oWaJ5mKvX3EuYVe4JUCV-QtrzAUziPF5iP~lh1aA07xK9VwZEESQB1jcrMsT4DPmwJPBXeSn9XwzeITn6qZ4jnA-LrTJA2AbfdAmewbqVDSS1fgYdXYRD8BlmMjHYj4WOjUbI3ddAwvJrKvLq-Ie~RxPo9NnwuTgYDYvjT9LxL~B44ZZJOsTHHW6cg5JCRaTYFzbl4DX0z51Eoc9UyS019tGmU8bSIVq2tqXyT8A1dOgHCteF7~-U38txu~H3kARg7iivuNOA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Responses to identical stimuli after dark and light adaptation. Flashes of white light (N=32; duration 130 ms; radiant power 20 μW; number of photons per flash 6.8×1012) were used. The ERGs obtained after increasing periods of darkness are depicted in A, whereas in B the matching control ERGs are shown (for the shifted vertically). The stimulation regimen was as follows: after 5 min of light adaptation (100 lx at the eye level of the pigeon), a control response was obtained. Then followed a period of darkness (given beside each trace in minutes), at the end of which an ERG was again measured. This was repeated a number of times with longer dark adaptation times. This type of measurement was often carried out prior to examining the effects of polarized light. It is obvious that the effect of dark adaptation under these circumstances is negligible, even for the longer periods of darkness. Although this procedure is not suited for gauging the rate of dark adaptation (the flashes were so intense that light adaptation was induced during the measurement of the ERG), it appears that dark adaptation is a slow process." path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" /></a><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a section="17082489" class="fig-view-orig" href="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=d~W00h7IpuUDobh6wWeG~W-VsKn490O~gijJd5B-JD-B7CEB6uKe4J8Sx~RlbFsZypjvk6SAtFeceI32U0cV5l8tbZz9QrzdZFsoC-fSfhP1khoa~u9BQpVJ0i~P9t6jcmZYN68sQ11exhnU5jd1wX1zxzcLz9dMtOy~mIpnqrWErqb3~uMicZZnb4de-0LNsZDdZsm81S-kM0AK7bUJsVGQakcAm8Y-gA9KMOYObvOWshwVjDUw0ITyW3VLSXqU9FV4iZ8xkfp3tQ0c9sXNE5fhYgkYuXNVgPjYpCi2lcKlUKq19HX-wE86V6htV3QszOI6onuRM4mlkAQeKazYCg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" target="_blank">View large</a><a section="17082489" href="//cob.silverchair-cdn.com/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f4.png?Expires=1716296304&Signature=d~W00h7IpuUDobh6wWeG~W-VsKn490O~gijJd5B-JD-B7CEB6uKe4J8Sx~RlbFsZypjvk6SAtFeceI32U0cV5l8tbZz9QrzdZFsoC-fSfhP1khoa~u9BQpVJ0i~P9t6jcmZYN68sQ11exhnU5jd1wX1zxzcLz9dMtOy~mIpnqrWErqb3~uMicZZnb4de-0LNsZDdZsm81S-kM0AK7bUJsVGQakcAm8Y-gA9KMOYObvOWshwVjDUw0ITyW3VLSXqU9FV4iZ8xkfp3tQ0c9sXNE5fhYgkYuXNVgPjYpCi2lcKlUKq19HX-wE86V6htV3QszOI6onuRM4mlkAQeKazYCg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=17082489&ar=7054&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=1000009" class="download-slide" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F4.tif" target="_blank">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p>Responses to identical stimuli after dark and light adaptation. Flashes of white light (<em>N</em>=32; duration 130 ms; radiant power 20 <em>μ</em>W; number of photons per flash 6.8×10<sup>12</sup>) were used. The ERGs obtained after increasing periods of darkness are depicted in A, whereas in B the matching control ERGs are shown (for the shifted vertically). The stimulation regimen was as follows: after 5 min of light adaptation (100 lx at the eye level of the pigeon), a control response was obtained. Then followed a period of darkness (given beside each trace in minutes), at the end of which an ERG was again measured. This was repeated a number of times with longer dark adaptation times. This type of measurement was often carried out prior to examining the effects of polarized light. It is obvious that the effect of dark adaptation under these circumstances is negligible, even for the longer periods of darkness. Although this procedure is not suited for gauging the rate of dark adaptation (the flashes were so intense that light adaptation was induced during the measurement of the ERG), it appears that dark adaptation is a slow process.</p></div><a class="close-reveal-modal" href="javascript:;"><i class="icon-general-close"> </i></a></div>
                </div>
                <div id="17082490" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082482">
                    
                    <p>In summary, neither a qualitative nor a quantitative evaluation of the processed ERG variables obtained in these pilot studies revealed a link between the state of polarization of the stimulus (orientation of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector, unpolarized or polarized) and the ERG response. Other features of the stimulus, such as colour or intensity, did, of course, influence the shape and characteristics of the ERG, but under all these conditions the state of polarization did not matter. These results, however, did indicate to us that experiments such as these must be set up carefully: changes in ERG characteristics in response to various states of polarization are apparently small in comparison with the variations caused by changes in the physiological conditions. We therefore started a series of experiments designed in such a manner that small differences in response to polarized stimuli could be detected better and, in addition, that would enable us to verify these differences statistically.</p>
                </div>
                </div>
                <h3 scrollto-destination="17082491" data-legacyid="s3b" id="17082491" data-section-title="Flashing stimuli" class="section-title ">Flashing stimuli</h3>
            <div >
                <div id="17082492" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082491">
                    
                    <p>Initially, we wanted to analyze our results using the method described by <a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325C14" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325C14" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Delius <em>et al</em>. (1976)</a>, so we evaluated the ERGs by visual inspection. In contrast to what they reported, however, we did not find that the shape of the b-wave depended on the orientation of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector.</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082493" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082491">
                    
                    <p>Because we recorded responses to only four standard orientations of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vector, we did not try to establish a relationship between the ERG features mentioned above and the stimulus angle based on periodicity. Instead, the ERG variables were determined for these angles and compared mutually by means of paired <em>t</em>-tests. For each session, we also compared the pooled responses to the polarized stimuli for each wavelength with the responses to the unpolarized stimuli.</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082494" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082491">
                    
                    <p>The ERG variables were measured under different conditions, yielding many combinations to be compared statistically to check the effect of polarization. The above-mentioned <em>t</em>-tests for paired comparisons yielded some significant differences (at the level of <em>P</em>=0.05), but statistical theory predicts that, if samples from two identical distributions are compared, the probability of cases in which the samples differ significantly is equal to the level of significance of the test involved. However, when the results that were apparently significant were compared with the results of other, identical experiments, it appeared that these occurrences were not systematic. Sometimes, the differences could be traced to abrupt changes in the physiological condition of the animal.</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082495" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082491">
                    
                    <p>Analysis of the latencies of the individual wavelets did not reveal differences between the responses to polarized and unpolarized stimuli (<a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5" href="javascript:;" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5" class="link link-reveal link-table xref-fig">Fig. 5</a>).</p>
                </div>
                <div id="17082496" class="article-section-wrapper js-article-section js-content-section  " data-section-parent-id="17082491">
                    
                    <a id = "17082496" scrollto-destination="17082496"></a><div data-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5" class="fig fig-section"><div class="label fig-label">Fig. 5.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><a reveal-id="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5" data-open="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5" class="fig-link"><img class="content-image" src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f5.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=DyX-0A256dm2MuF2PfnLzbZmiWs1tmgcI1feISUUljiAfS5ENqHqz07Yv27rW-wZYWKiebiUkub~qOUAenM6D~Mo036mR8UOqCILRwvYggRWAmtzhrF1K7H~2GnHkqes3yy8rghFwiOcnV4wwg0k2wMqSE12RwMsqFvWIzGECz5QfHranCWO0vh3bkWLVlPZCsizda~Z4E~wuuRdjEUT~yZkDrY84eJMf6N1~UB5Qj0pgUsH4K4WRx1LjxNJ0eFaynWzpu27eU9Q0dMmBlVPFx73sbTwS8s2pXJaKeqT1MM2FmhDwOxpC9vWezE1k~Renrmf8J2hpTRF6XKL6sFPUQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" data-src="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/m_jexbio_198_2_325f5.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=DyX-0A256dm2MuF2PfnLzbZmiWs1tmgcI1feISUUljiAfS5ENqHqz07Yv27rW-wZYWKiebiUkub~qOUAenM6D~Mo036mR8UOqCILRwvYggRWAmtzhrF1K7H~2GnHkqes3yy8rghFwiOcnV4wwg0k2wMqSE12RwMsqFvWIzGECz5QfHranCWO0vh3bkWLVlPZCsizda~Z4E~wuuRdjEUT~yZkDrY84eJMf6N1~UB5Qj0pgUsH4K4WRx1LjxNJ0eFaynWzpu27eU9Q0dMmBlVPFx73sbTwS8s2pXJaKeqT1MM2FmhDwOxpC9vWezE1k~Renrmf8J2hpTRF6XKL6sFPUQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Latencies of oscillatory potentials elicited by flashes (140 ms) of white light (A) and by monochromatic light of 393 nm (B). Filled circles show the responses to reference stimuli, whereas the arrows show responses to polarized light, with the angle of the symbol denoting the orientation of the E-vector (see Fig. 1). The centre part of the retina, near the fovea, was stimulated; the radiant power was 6 μW for both types of stimuli (2.2×1012 and 1.7×1012 photons per flash, respectively). The latencies following 393 nm flashes are longer than those following stimulation with white light. There is no relationship between the latencies of the oscillatory potentials and the orientation of the E-vector." path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5.tif" /></a><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a section="17082496" class="fig-view-orig" href="https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f5.png?Expires=1716296304&amp;Signature=iZmQ2VZx6ycs2dKpHfzq0WsX1egyhavBYXxuPC~FZPJwN7uI2K1Cx4UNwRTsoGV1tuL9AjpuKCn-if-PpMrQwoSiID7~OCMS9T9N-3YmNVq33KS0KmWR~A3XSyfY4b4ifx1w4ONrzks~AQe5Bprrzt1~2~gScOjrXj~-ngTeIyedLgl6UlkFbm~YxHlaD0uE9sj-kLSuj0pbCY~Cb8Pnsib4i9ZckdRN6Lx1lR7nXZBALrE2NTDYPtMeAMZM1ekGwzEapKvZms00bS8NZAhzU7Mnl5p~NcqqAaroFKR4pMU~uqIDRnaqC88gJx8FAttHUJuE-MNxCeZY1GKQyUJDLg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5.tif" target="_blank">View large</a><a section="17082496" href="//cob.silverchair-cdn.com/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://cob.silverchair-cdn.com/cob/content_public/journal/jeb/198/2/10.1242_jeb.198.2.325/5/jexbio_198_2_325f5.png?Expires=1716296304&Signature=iZmQ2VZx6ycs2dKpHfzq0WsX1egyhavBYXxuPC~FZPJwN7uI2K1Cx4UNwRTsoGV1tuL9AjpuKCn-if-PpMrQwoSiID7~OCMS9T9N-3YmNVq33KS0KmWR~A3XSyfY4b4ifx1w4ONrzks~AQe5Bprrzt1~2~gScOjrXj~-ngTeIyedLgl6UlkFbm~YxHlaD0uE9sj-kLSuj0pbCY~Cb8Pnsib4i9ZckdRN6Lx1lR7nXZBALrE2NTDYPtMeAMZM1ekGwzEapKvZms00bS8NZAhzU7Mnl5p~NcqqAaroFKR4pMU~uqIDRnaqC88gJx8FAttHUJuE-MNxCeZY1GKQyUJDLg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=17082496&ar=7054&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=1000009" class="download-slide" path-from-xml="JEXBIO_198_2_325F5.tif" target="_blank">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p>Latencies of oscillatory potentials elicited by flashes (140 ms) of white light (A) and by monochromatic light of 393 nm (B). Filled circles show the responses to reference stimuli, whereas the arrows show responses to polarized light, with the angle of the symbol denoting the orientation of the <strong><em>E</em></strong>-vecto